y at the turn of the century, turning it into a modern fighting force and the nation into a world power.Throughout his life, Wood tested the division between military and civilian power to its very limits. His 1920 presidential campaign and his conflicts with civilian politicians were harbingers of the struggles that Generals Douglas MacArthur and Dwight D. Eisenhower would face as they moved from the battlefield to Washington following World War II.Jack McCallum has mined Wood's extensive personal records-including diaries, correspondence, and photographs-to create a vivid portrait of a complex man and the legacy he left on U.S. imperialism. America's rapid conquest of Cuba and the Philippines and the subsequent political and economic reconstruction it imposed under Wood's military supervision in these regions have important parallels to current U.S. involvement in the Middle East, both in its successes and its failures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aGeneralszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aGovernors generalzPhilippinesvBiography. 0aMilitary governorszCubavBiography. 0aPresidential candidateszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aSpanish-American War, 1898vBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aJack.  aMcCallum.  aUS.  aWoods.  acomplex.  acreate.  aextensive.  aimperialism.  aleft.  alegacy.  amined.  apersonal.  aportrait.  arecords.  avivid.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759806/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL